{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "True, it rarely comes to full-blown deception, where users actually believe that the systems they are interacting with are human-like entities with feelings and emotions.",
    "However, another kind of deception seems to occur, where the user \"has a rational appreciation of the nature of the device it interacts with but at a subconscious level cannot help reacting to it as if it is real\" (Saetra 2021, p. 282).",
    "This seems to be exactly what happens with affective artificial agents.",
    "Most users arguably know that it is just about simulating emotions.",
    "And yet, in their interactions with the systems, their emotional responses are comparable to the ones they would have were they interacting with a human, to the point that these interactions can result in the formation of deep emotional bonds."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "However, another kind of deception seems to occur, where the user \"has a rational appreciation of the nature of the device it interacts with but at a subconscious level cannot help reacting to it as if it is real\" (Saetra 2021, p. 282)."
